<h2>
    Local Angler Advice
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Reddit tip</strong>: For a fun scouting trip, explore different holes on the North Santiam around Stayton—waders help a lot. Visit Marion Forks and try a guide for a smooth learning curve 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Coho surge</strong>: Recent years have seen strong Coho returns up the Santiam and into the Willamette, offering excellent fall fishing opportunities .
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Quick Tips for Success
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Licensing</strong>: Oregon angling license + Combined Tag required; check steelhead/salmon retention rules on ODFW.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear</strong>: Medium-heavy rod (7–9 ft), 12–20 lb test. Use plugs (Kwikfish), spinners, flasher‑roe rigs.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boat Access</strong>: Helpful in Santiam tributaries and Siuslaw; bank fishing works well near bridges and calm seams.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Bait &amp; Gear Seasons</strong>: Bait open in spring/summer on Santiam; artificial only in restricted zones.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Flow &amp; Conditions</strong>: Ideal flows vary—spring Chinook prefer clear moderate flows, fall Coho like cooler water after rains.
    </li>
</ol>

